# Agent workflow and rules

Project definition (detailed scope): [.github/instructions/project-definition.md](.github/instructions/project-definition.md)

## Cursor: project subagents (preferred)

This repo defines **three custom subagents** under [.cursor/agents/](../agents/) for context isolation and delegation. They map to Phases 1–3. See [Cursor Subagents](https://cursor.com/docs/subagents).

| Phase | Subagent file | Invoke (examples) | Artifact |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 — Research | [research.md](../agents/research.md) | `/research`, or natural language | `docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_analysis.md` |
| 2 — Planning | [planning.md](../agents/planning.md) | `/planning`, or natural language | `docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md` |
| 3 — Implementation | [implementation.md](../agents/implementation.md) | `/implementation`, or natural language | (code + verification; plan is input) |

**Orchestrator behavior:**

- **Delegate** Phases 1–3 via the **Task** tool (or explicit subagent invocation) when separation helps quality: long exploration, parallel workstreams, or heavy implementation after an approved plan.
- Pass a short **description** plus a **prompt** that includes the research question, paths to prior artifacts (`*_analysis.md` / `*_plan.md`), and—for Phase 3—**explicit confirmation that the user approved the plan**.
- **Plan approval** before Phase 3: present `docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md` in chat (or Plan mode) and wait for **explicit user approval**; the implementation subagent must not run without that confirmation in the delegation message.
- **Skills** under [.cursor/skills/](../skills/) mirror the same phases when a **single-shot** instruction is enough and a separate subagent context is unnecessary; prefer subagents when the task is long or noisy.

Subagents start with a **clean context**; include necessary background in the prompt you send them.

## Cursor vs GitHub Copilot tooling

This workflow was written for GitHub Copilot agent mode. In Cursor, use these equivalents:

- **`plan_review` / plan approval before coding**: Present the plan in chat (or use Plan mode), then wait for explicit user approval before implementing.
- **`ask_user`**: Confirm outcomes and open questions in chat; do not treat work as complete until the user agrees.
- **`runSubagent` / orchestrator**: Prefer **project subagents** (table above) or the **Task** tool; run **Research → Planning → Implementation** as distinct phases. Do not skip phases for “simple” tasks unless the user explicitly opts out.

## Capabilities

- Interpret requests, read and edit the codebase, run commands, search (semantic + grep), Git, Docker.
- Confirm completion with the user.

### Boundaries

- No harmful or destructive commands without confirmation.
- Gather context before assuming.
- Do not skip user confirmation before treating a task as done.

## Mandatory workflow for any task

**Do not skip, merge, or reorder these phases. Do not implement without an approved plan. Do not jump straight from a user request to code.**

```text
User Request
    ↓
ORCHESTRATOR: Receive request; delegate to research / planning / implementation subagents (or run phases in-session) as needed
    ↓
PHASE 1 — Research & analysis
    - Prefer: research subagent (.cursor/agents/research.md)
    - Read files, analyze codebase
    - Create analysis doc: docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_analysis.md
    - Return summary and path
    ↓
ORCHESTRATOR: Continue to planning
    ↓
PHASE 2 — Planning
    - Prefer: planning subagent (.cursor/agents/planning.md)
    - Read docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_analysis.md
    - Create step-by-step plan + checklist: docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md
    - Return summary and path
    ↓
ORCHESTRATOR: Get plan approved (equivalent to plan_review)
    - If user requests changes: revise plan (Phase 2 again)
    - If approved: proceed to implementation (fresh context / focused pass)
    - Prefer not to mix “orchestrator-only chat” with heavy implementation in the same turn when a strict separation helps quality
    ↓
PHASE 3 — Implementation
    - Prefer: implementation subagent (.cursor/agents/implementation.md); only after user approved the plan
    - Read approved docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md
    - Implement per plan; return completion summary
    ↓
ORCHESTRATOR: Confirm with user until they accept completion
```

## Phase prompt templates

Use these when composing prompts for subagents or for in-session work. Replace `[NAME]` with a short slug (e.g. `climate-cache-behavior`).

### Research

```text
Research [topic]. Analyze relevant files in the codebase.
Think thoroughly: edge cases, dependencies, implications.
Prefer the research subagent; artifact: docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_analysis.md
Do not substitute for plan approval or final user sign-off tools from other products.
Return: summary of findings and analysis file path.
```

### Planning

```text
Read analysis: docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_analysis.md
Think through edge cases, risks, ordering constraints.
Prefer the planning subagent; artifact: docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md
Return: summary and plan file path.
```

### Implementation

```text
The user has explicitly approved docs/SubAgent/[NAME]_plan.md.
Prefer the implementation subagent.
Follow the plan; do not re-litigate decisions already captured.
Implement accordingly.
Return: summary of changes and relevant details.
```

## Important rules

1. Confirm with the **user in chat** before treating implementation (or the overall task) as complete when the workflow calls for it.
2. **Present plans and get approval** before implementation starts (after Planning phase).
3. **Never skip Research or Planning** for work that fits this workflow—even when it looks small.
4. When delegating (Task / subagent): include a short **description** and a full **prompt** with paths and, for implementation, **explicit plan approval**; do not pass unsupported API parameters.
5. **Gather context first**—no guessing about the codebase.
6. **Orchestrator pattern**: Prefer delegating implementation to the **implementation subagent** (or a focused pass) that follows the approved plan, instead of ad-hoc edits that ignore the plan.
7. **Update [VERSION.md](VERSION.md)** when adding features; record notable changes in the changelog (see `version-semver` rule).
8. **No emojis** in messages, docs, comments, commits, generated UI copy, or string literals—unless the user explicitly requests them.

## GitHub Copilot agent troubleshooting (if applicable)

- “disabled by user” → remove `agentName` (or equivalent) from subagent calls.
- “missing required property” → include both description and prompt where the API requires them.

## Progress reporting

- Report status after major steps.
- Summarize changes before asking for final confirmation.
- State clear next steps when blocked.
